+slobomotion It is. They took Samuel Fuller's original script and re-did 
some of the lines and scene placement to reflect the setting (Cape Town 
rather than New York City). Other than that, it's the original verbatim.

To me, only James Brolin really does nearly as well as his American 
predecessor (Richard Widmark); in fact, many of his line readings sound 
like Widmark's original. Claire Trevor does pretty well as Sam, but not 
nearly as well as Thelma Ritter as Moe. Jacqueline Bisset is very good as 
Candy (and very beautiful), but her line readings sometimes sound stilted; 
Jean Peters sounds much more natural.

Nonetheless, this is a good movie which I enjoyed watching very much!!!!! 
Thank you, Grindhouse Guru, for sharing this with us!!!!!

This is a very significant film - it marks the first time that an 
international film of any kind was filmed in Cape Town, and pays the 
sublime compliment of using the real city, real buildings and real 
locations to give what would ordinarily be a B-grade spy movie an air of 
great sophistication. To this day in Cape Town the phone booth where 
Jacqueline Bisset use still stands on Adderly Street. Josh Brolin's hut at 
the V&A Waterfront is no more, sadly. Many good South African actors got a 
splash from this film - Gordon Mulholland has had a vibrant career of 
nearly 50 years thanks to this film, becoming one of South African cinema's 
'Grand Old Men' in the process. The drama is tight, and so loses very 
little. And in South Africa, during my youth and childhood, communist 
infiltration and undermining was a concern, though much overblown, and 
crafted into a tool of repression. Despite its age, it is very interesting 
film to gain a view of the Cape Town that was....and whose bones are still 
to be seen to this day.﻿
